Minor Races of Aetheria
They are far fewer in number than the major races and usually exist in scattered communities, enclaves, or as minorities within larger kingdoms.

Merfolk & Azure Folk (Aquatic)
Live in underwater cities, floating isles, and coastal reefs.
Society: Matriarchal clans ruled by song-mages. Highly artistic, trade-focused, and isolationist.
Culture: Emphasize beauty, music, and fluid hierarchies. Lifespan ~150–300 years.
Interactions: Trade pearls, coral magic, and sea goods with humans and elves. Suspicious of dwarves (who “steal from the deep”). Frequent raids from demonic sea-beasts. Sometimes enslave shipwrecked humans.

Gnomes
Small, clever tinkerers living in hidden hill burrows or ruined Golden Age workshops.
Society: Loose inventor guilds. Decisions made by merit and wild experimentation.
Culture: Obsessed with mechanisms, illusions, and pranks. Lifespan ~250–400 years.
Interactions: Hired as engineers by humans and dwarves. Viewed as amusing but untrustworthy by elves. Beastkin see them as tasty snacks if caught. Often enslaved for their technical skills.

Halflings (Riverfolk / Burrowers)
Peaceful, short-statured farmers and traders living in river valleys and peaceful shires.
Society: Tight-knit family clans with elected elders.
Culture: Value comfort, good food, stories, and avoiding trouble. Lifespan ~90–130 years.
Interactions: Excellent merchants tolerated by everyone. Humans and Beastkin often protect (or exploit) them. Rarely enslaved due to low value in labor or war, but easy targets for raids.

Orcs & Goblinoids
Brutal, tribal warriors living in badlands, mountains, and demonic border wastes.
Society: Strong chieftain rule. Constant internal challenges for leadership.
Culture: Honor through combat and survival. Lifespan ~60–90 years.
Interactions: Sometimes hired as mercenaries by human March lords. Mostly enemies to all races, since they raid kill, but are not organized. Population usually controlled by the Adventurers & Mercenary Guild. Hated by elves and dwarves. Some clans have uneasy alliances with demons; others fight them bitterly. Common source of arena slaves.

Fae (True Fairies & Sprites)
Tiny winged or nature-attuned spirits living in deep forests and ancient ruins.
Society: Court-based under Seelie (summer) and Unseelie (winter) rulers. Capricious and political.
Culture: Masters of illusion, emotion, and dream magic. Extremely long-lived (centuries).
Interactions: Allies with High Forest Elves. Play cruel tricks on humans and Beastkin. Avoid dwarves. Occasionally make pacts with demons for power. Highly sought after for exotic slavery (as pets or mages).

Centaurs
Proud nomadic horse-people of the plains and steppes.
Society: Herd-based with strong warrior traditions and shaman elders.
Culture: Value freedom, archery, and storytelling. Lifespan ~120–180 years.
Interactions: Trade and skirmish with Beastkin and humans. Respect dwarven craftsmanship. Dislike elven arrogance. Sometimes serve as elite cavalry mercenaries for human kingdoms. Get extremly offended if humans call them Horse Beastfolk or when thought as part of the Beastkin people

Cambions & Tieflings (Demon-Blooded)
Human-demon (or other mortal-demon) hybrids. Live in border zones or hidden communities.
Society: Tight-knit outcast groups or individuals integrated into demonic courts.
Culture: Varied — some embrace infernal heritage, others reject it. Often melancholic or ambitious.
Interactions: Distrusted or persecuted by all major races. Valued as diplomats or spies by humans. Hated by elves and dwarves. Welcomed (or exploited) by demons. Frequent targets of purges and slavery.

General Notes on Minor Races

Most minor races have low magic aptitude (except Fae and gnome(weak aptitude)) and rely on niche strengths for survival.
Slavery is extremely common for them — they are seen as “in-between” peoples and easier to subjugate than major races.
Intermarriage is rare but produces unique bloodlines (e.g., half-halfling merchants or orc-beastkin berserkers).
In human kingdoms they often form guilds or ghetto districts. Elves tolerate only Fae and select others in their enclaves. Dwarves accept gnomes and halflings as useful workers. Beastkin are generally hostile unless the minor race proves strength.
